  <title>Adjusting Transparency</title>

  <media type="image" src="figures/transparency.png">
    <p>Making the ruler semitransparent</p>
  </media>

  <p>
    To help you measure objects behind the ruler, you can adjust the ruler's opacity.
    By making the ruler semitransparent, you can see the objects behind the ruler.
  </p>

  <steps>
    <item><p>Click the menu button (<media its:translate="no" type="image" src="figures/open-menu-symbolic.svg"/>) in the left-side corner of the ruler.</p></item>

    <item>
      <p>
        Adjust the opacity percentage.
        A 100% opacity means that the ruler is not transparent at all, and it masks the objects behind it.
        Because a 0% opacity would render the ruler completely transparent, you cannot reduce the opacity below 10%.
      </p>
    </item>
  </steps>

  <p>Alternatively, you can adjust the opacity by using the arrow keys: <key>Left</key> or <key>Down</key> to reduce the opacity and render the ruler semitransparent, and <key>Right</key> or <key>Up</key> to increase the opacity.</p>

  <p>To prevent the object to measure from covering the ruler, right click the ruler and select <gui style="menuitem">Always on Top</gui>:</p>

  <media type="image" src="figures/always-on-top.png">
    <p>Use the context menu and select <gui style="menuitem">Always on Top</gui>.</p>
  </media>
